Oct 11 2007 	Really liked the Piccolino	Piccolino Hotel, a little 3 star jewel, is one of a number of hotels (#14) on Sussex Place in Paddington, very close to the tube station in an excellent location for central London. This is a relatively quiet area and a terrific launching point for almost any sightseeing you wish to do. What I feel differentiates the Piccolino from many of the others, however, is its friendly staff (thanks to Tanveer, Waqas, Azeem) and cleanliness, its hardwood floors giving it a rather rustic appeal. Whether you pay 60 GBP or 260 GBP a night in London, you are likely to come away just as dissatisfied with many of the hotels whatever the cost, due to a lack of service, unresponsive staff, or other difficulties. For instance, around the corner from the Piccolino at the Adare Hotel, which is identically priced but whose rooms are filthy, you would be frightened to get into bed, let alone sleep on the bed. At the Adare, also, I’m not even sure that the doors lock.Having just spent three nights at the Piccolino, I was extremely pleased with how kind the staff all were and how clean the rooms and baths were – great hot water, clean sheets and pillows, enough space to not be bumping into each other, etc. If you should encounter any kind of problem, the reception desk seems to immediately want to take care of you and fix whatever is needed. While I did not tour every room in the Piccolino, I found my accommodations quite satisfactory, comparing it to other European hotels. Reception is also willing to store your luggage if you are early for your room or if you need to check out but have a later flight. Breakfast is included in the price with a good selection of food offerings to get you going in the mornings. This breakfast, I might add, is more aimed at those who want an early go at sightseeing – it is not intended for those who want to sleep in, who can find alternative eats nearby. A couple of blocks down toward the tube station, there is an internet café and other little eateries and convenience stores in a straight line to the tube although you have wireless access in your room. Having flown in on EasyJet, I decided to travel to the Piccolino on the little 5 minute free shuttle from Luton to the train station, which I took for what seemed like hours, transferring then to the tube to Paddington. On my departure, I simply took the tube to Baker St., walked a couple of blocks, and jumped right on the Green Line Bus, which comes and goes straight to Luton, so much easier and cheaper. EasyJet also has a special internet offer for the Green Line, which is a great value and the least hassle. Altogether, the two questions I always ask myself: can I comfortably recommend this little hotel to others? Absolutely. Would I stay here myself again? Absolutely.	
